-- Japanese Stocks Advance on Earnings Outlook, U.S. Takeovers; KDDI Jumps
-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 2011-02-08T07:31:15Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-08/japan-stocks-rise-for-third-day-mitsui-mining-japan-tobacco-lead-advance.html
Japan’s stocks gained for a third day,
as an improved earnings outlook and U.S. takeovers bolstered
investors’ confidence the global recovery will be sustained.  KDDI Corp., Japan’s second-largest mobile-phone operator,
jumped 5.8 percent after it was boosted to “outperform” by
Credit Suisse Group AG. Nippon Meat Packers Inc., Japan’s
biggest producer of ham and sausage, rose 6.6 percent after
increasing its full-year profit forecast. Mitsubishi Estate Co.,
Japan’s No. 2 developer, gained 2.1 percent after CLSA Asia-
Pacific Markets raised its share-price estimate. Sumitomo Mitsui
Financial Group Inc., Japan’s second-largest publicly traded
bank, gained 2.3 percent amid lenders’ reports of higher profits.  “Earnings are solid in Japan,” and the global economic
outlook has been positive, said Naoteru Teraoka, general manager
at Tokyo-based Chuo Mitsui Asset Management Co., which oversees
about $26 billion. “Stocks are reacting to positive news.”  The  Nikkei 225  Stock Average rose 0.4 percent to 10,635.98
in Tokyo, the highest close since May 6. Its spread between the
intraday high and low was 25 yen, the narrowest range since
February 10, 1986, according data compiled by Bloomberg. The
broader Topix index gained 0.4 percent to 944, with about three
stocks climbing for every four that fell.  KDDI leapt 5.8 percent to 506,000 yen and was the biggest
contributor to the Nikkei 225’s advance, after Credit Suisse
Group AG boosted its rating on the stock to “outperform” from
“neutral.” Nissan Motor Co. climbed 0.5 percent to 871 yen
after it was raised to “outperform” by CLSA.  Nippon Meat  Fujikura Ltd., a cable maker, jumped 7.7 percent to 447 yen
after JPMorgan Chase & Co. raised its stock-price estimate to
400 yen from 380 yen. Fujikura said nine-month net income rose
1.8 percent.  Nippon Meat Packers Inc., Japan’s biggest producer of ham
and sausage, jumped 6.6 percent to 1,196 yen, the second-
steepest gain on the Nikkei 225. The company said net income for
the nine months ended Dec. 31 surged 15 percent from a year
earlier, and raised its full-year net income forecast by 7.7
percent to 14 billion yen ($170 million).  Horiba Ltd., a maker of measuring instruments, gained 6.7
percent to 2,552 yen after boosting its full-year net income
outlook 37 percent.  The Topix rose 4.6 percent this year to yesterday, compared
with gains of 4.9 percent by the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index and
4.7 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the
Japanese benchmark were valued at 16.1 times estimated earnings
on average, compared with about 13.7 times for the  S&P 500  and
11.4 times for the Stoxx 600.  Mitsubishi Estate  Futures on the S&P 500 were little changed today. The index
rose 0.6 percent in New York yesterday after Danaher Corp.
agreed to acquire Beckman Coulter Inc. for $6.8 billion, and
Ensco Plc said it will buy Pride International Inc. for $7.3
billion.  “As global competition intensifies, strategic M&A that is
aimed at strengthening competitiveness by expanding the scale of
operations is spreading globally,”  Mitsushige Akino , who
oversees about $450 million in Tokyo at Ichiyoshi Investment
Management Co. “The trend has economic rationality, so that’s
positive for the stock market.”  Mitsubishi Estate rose 2.1 percent to 1,638 yen, after CLSA
raised its share-price estimate to 1,900 yen from 1,785 yen.
Mitsui Fudosan Co. gained 0.1 percent to 1,705 yen. CLSA raised
its estimated share price to 1,875 yen from 1,780 yen.  Bank Earnings  Banks extended yesterday’s gains, with Sumitomo Mitsui
rising 2.3 percent to 2,977 yen. Mizuho Financial Group Inc.,
Japan’s No. 3 bank by market value, advanced 3.1 percent to 169
yen, while Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group Inc., the No. 1, rose
2 percent to 456 yen. A measure of banks was the biggest
contributor to the Topix’s advance.  Of the 65 banks that have reported results since Jan. 1 for
the latest quarter, 17 have beat analysts’ estimates, while 4
have missed them, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  As of 4:18 p.m. in Tokyo, 124 of the 1,668 companies in the
Topix index were scheduled to release earnings statements today.
Of the 1,121 that have reported results since Jan. 1 for the
latest quarter, 152 exceeded analysts’ estimates, while 113
missed them, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Japan’s current account surplus widened in December as the
global recovery boosted demand for the nation’s products. The
gap expanded 30.5 percent from a year earlier to 1.195 trillion
yen, the  Finance Ministry  said today in Tokyo. The median
estimate of 25 economists surveyed by Bloomberg News was for a
surplus of 1.13 trillion yen.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Tokyo at 
